# RedNote Operation — Cursor Rules

## Branch Strategy
- Always branch from latest `main`: `git checkout main && git pull`
- Branch naming: `<type>/<scope>-<description>`
  - `feat/crawl-notes`, `fix/browser-timeout`, `feat/knowledge-food-templates`, `docs/agents`
- NEVER commit directly to `main`
- Each branch = single concern, max 10 file changes

## Commit Convention
Format: `<type>(<scope>): <description>`
Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `chore`, `test`
Scopes: `core`, `scripts`, `crawl`, `analyze`, `create`, `publish`, `web`, `browser`, `db`, `config`, `knowledge`, `skills`
Use imperative mood, lowercase, no period at end.
Examples:
- `feat(crawl): add note collection with keyword filtering`
- `fix(browser): handle login session expiry`
- `feat(knowledge): add post templates for food category`

## Pre-commit Verification
- Always run `pre-commit run --all-files` before committing
- Fix all lint/type errors before pushing
- Never skip pre-commit checks

## Pre-push Verification
- Pushing to `main` triggers full test suite
- Ensure all tests pass before merging PR

## Workflow
1. `git checkout main && git pull`
2. `git checkout -b <type>/<scope>-<description>`
3. Implement changes
4. `pre-commit run --all-files` — fix any issues
5. `git add . && git commit -m "<type>(<scope>): <description>"`
6. `git push origin <branch-name>` — creates remote branch
7. Create PR on GitHub → wait for CI → merge
8. `git checkout main && git pull`
9. Delete local branch: `git branch -d <branch-name>`
